  "topic": "Portuguese Future Tense (Futuro do Presente)",
  "language_pair": "en-pt",
  "target_language": "pt",
  "native_language": "en",
  "description": "Portuguese Future Tense (Futuro do Presente) – for English speakers. Used for future actions, predictions, intentions, promises, and spontaneous decisions. It is very similar to English 'will' + verb, but Portuguese has its own regular endings and many irregular verbs. In spoken Brazilian Portuguese, people often use 'ir + infinitive' (vou fazer) for near future / plans instead of the synthetic future.",
  "grammar_focus": {
    "rule": "Infinitive stem + future endings (-ei, -ás, -á, -emos, -ão) added directly to the full infinitive (regular pattern)",
    "suffixes": {
      "eu (I)": "-ei",
      "tu (you informal)": "-ás",
      "você/ele/ela (you formal/he/she/it)": "-á",
      "nós (we)": "-emos",
      "vocês/eles/elas (you plural/they)": "-ão"
    },
    "note_en": "The future tense is formed by adding endings directly to the infinitive (falar → falarei, comer → comerei, partir → partirei). Very common irregular stems: dizer → direi, fazer → farei, trazer → trarei, poder → poderei, saber → saberei, caber → caberei, haver → haverei, etc. In everyday Brazilian Portuguese, 'vou + infinitive' is much more frequent for plans and near future (Vou comer = I'm going to eat / I'll eat). The synthetic future (falarei) is more formal, literary, or used for predictions and promises. Negation: não + future verb. Questions: intonation or inversion (Você virá?)."
  },
